# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tone-mapping
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] A **display device** is an output device for presentation of information in visual or tactile form (the latter used for example in tactile electronic displays for blind people).
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] When the input information that is supplied has an electrical signal the display is called an *electronic display*.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] Common applications for *electronic visual displays* are television sets or computer monitors.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] These are the technologies used to create the various displays in use today.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] Some displays can show only digits or alphanumeric characters.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] They are called **segment displays**, because they are composed of several segments that switch on and off to give appearance of desired glyph.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] The segments are usually single LEDs or liquid crystals.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] They are mostly used in digital watches and pocket calculators.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] Common types are seven-segment displays which are used for numerals only, and alphanumeric fourteen-segment displays and sixteen-segment displays which can display numerals and Roman alphabet letters.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] Cathode-ray tubes were also formerly widely used.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] 2-dimensional displays that cover a full area (usually a rectangle) are also called **video displays**, since it is the main modality of presenting video.
[src:tone-mapping/display-device] The multiplexed display technique is used to drive most display devices.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In photography, **exposure** is the amount of light per unit area reaching a frame of photographic film or the surface of an electronic image sensor.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] It is determined by exposure time, lens f-number, and scene luminance.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Exposure is measured in units of lux-seconds (symbol lx⋅s), and can be computed from exposure value (EV) and scene luminance in a specified region.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] An "exposure" is a single shutter cycle.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] For example, a long exposure refers to a single, long shutter cycle to gather enough dim light, whereas a multiple exposure involves a series of shutter cycles, effectively layering a series of photographs in one image.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The accumulated *photometric exposure* (*H*v) is the same so long as the total exposure time is the same.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Only in this appropriately weighted case does the H measure the effective amount of light falling on the film, such that the characteristic curve will be correct independent of the spectrum of the light.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Many photographic materials are also sensitive to "invisible" light, which can be a nuisance , or a benefit .
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The use of radiometric units is appropriate to characterize such sensitivity to invisible light.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In sensitometric data, such as characteristic curves, the *log exposure* is conventionally expressed as log10(*H*).
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Photographers more familiar with base-2 logarithmic scales (such as exposure values) can convert using log2(*H*) ≈ 3.32 log10(*H*).
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] So-called "correct" exposure may be defined as an exposure that achieves the effect the photographer intended.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] A more technical approach recognises that a photographic film (or sensor) has a physically limited useful exposure range, sometimes called its dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] If, for any part of the photograph, the actual exposure is outside this range, the film cannot record it accurately.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In a very simple model, for example, out-of-range values would be recorded as "black" (underexposed) or "white" (overexposed) rather than the precisely graduated shades of colour and tone required to describe "detail".
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Therefore, the purpose of exposure adjustment (and/or lighting adjustment) is to control the physical amount of light from the subject that is allowed to fall on the film, so that 'significant' areas of shadow and highlight detail do not exceed the film's useful exposure range.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] This ensures that no 'significant' information is lost during capture.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The photographer may carefully overexpose or underexpose the photograph to *eliminate* what they judge as insignificant or unwanted detail; to make, for example, a white altar cloth appear immaculately clean, or to emulate the heavy, pitiless shadows of film noir.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] However, it is technically much easier to discard recorded information during post processing than to try to 're-create' unrecorded information.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In a scene with strong or harsh lighting, the *ratio* between highlight and shadow luminance values may well be larger than the ratio between the film's maximum and minimum useful exposure values.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *overexposed* when it has a loss of highlight detail, that is, when important bright parts of an image are "washed out" or effectively all white, known as "blown-out highlights" or "clipped whites".
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *underexposed* when it has a loss of shadow detail, that is, when important dark areas are "muddy" or indistinguishable from black, known as "blocked-up shadows" (or sometimes "crushed shadows", "crushed blacks", or "clipped blacks", especially in video).
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] As the adjacent image shows, these terms are technical ones rather than artistic judgments; an overexposed or underexposed image may be "correct" in the sense that it provides the effect that the photographer intended.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Intentionally over- or underexposing (relative to a standard or the camera's automatic exposure) is casually referred to as "exposing to the right" or "exposing to the left" respectively, as these shift the histogram of the image to the right or left.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In manual mode, the photographer adjusts the lens aperture and/or shutter speed to achieve the desired exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Many photographers choose to control aperture and shutter independently because opening up the aperture increases exposure, but also decreases the depth of field, and a slower shutter increases exposure but also increases the opportunity for motion blur.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] "Manual" exposure calculations may be based on some method of light metering with a working knowledge of exposure values, the APEX system and/or the Zone System.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] A camera in **automatic exposure** or **autoexposure** (usually initialized as **AE**) mode automatically calculates and adjusts exposure settings to match (as closely as possible) the subject's mid-tone to the mid-tone of the photograph.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] For most cameras, this means using an on-board TTL exposure meter.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Aperture priority (commonly abbreviated as *A*, or *Av* for "aperture value") mode gives the photographer manual control of the aperture, whilst the camera automatically adjusts the shutter speed to achieve the exposure specified by the TTL meter.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Shutter priority (often abbreviated as *S*, or *Tv* for "time value") mode gives manual shutter control, with automatic aperture compensation.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In each case, the actual exposure level is still determined by the camera's exposure meter.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The purpose of an exposure meter is to estimate the subject's mid-tone luminance and indicate the camera exposure settings required to record this as a mid-tone.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In order to do this it has to make a number of assumptions which, under certain circumstances, will be wrong.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] If the exposure setting indicated by an exposure meter is taken as the "reference" exposure, the photographer may wish to deliberately *overexpose* or *underexpose* in order to compensate for known or anticipated metering inaccuracies.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Cameras with any kind of internal exposure meter usually feature an exposure compensation setting which is intended to allow the photographer to simply offset the exposure level from the internal meter's estimate of appropriate exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Frequently calibrated in stops, also known as EV units, a "+1" exposure compensation setting indicates one stop more (twice as much) exposure and "−1" means one stop less (half as much) exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Exposure compensation is particularly useful in combination with auto-exposure mode, as it allows the photographer to *bias* the exposure level without resorting to full manual exposure and losing the flexibility of auto exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] On low-end video camcorders, exposure compensation may be the only manual exposure control available.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] An appropriate exposure for a photograph is determined by the sensitivity of the medium used.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] For photographic film, sensitivity is referred to as film speed and is measured on a scale published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Faster film, that is, film with a higher ISO rating, requires less exposure to make a readable image.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Digital cameras usually have variable ISO settings that provide additional flexibility.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Exposure is a combination of the length of time and the illuminance at the photosensitive material.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Exposure time is controlled in a camera by shutter speed, and the illuminance depends on the lens aperture and the scene luminance.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Slower shutter speeds (exposing the medium for a longer period of time), greater lens apertures (admitting more light), and higher-luminance scenes produce greater exposures.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] An approximately correct exposure will be obtained on a sunny day using ISO 100 film, an aperture of f/16 and a shutter speed of 1⁄100 of a second.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] This is called the sunny 16 rule: at an aperture of f/16 on a sunny day, a suitable shutter speed will be one over the film speed (or closest equivalent).
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] A scene can be exposed in many ways, depending on the desired effect a photographer wishes to convey.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] An important principle of exposure is reciprocity.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] If one exposes the film or sensor for a longer period, a reciprocally smaller aperture is required to reduce the amount of light hitting the film to obtain the same exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] For example, the photographer may prefer to make their sunny-16 shot at an aperture of f/5.6 (to obtain a shallow depth of field).
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] As f/5.6 is 3 **stops** "faster" than f/16, with each stop meaning double the amount of light, a new shutter speed of (1⁄125)/(2·2·2) = 1⁄1000 s is needed.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Once the photographer has determined the exposure, aperture stops can be traded for halvings or doublings of speed, within limits.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The true characteristic of most photographic emulsions is not actually linear (see sensitometry), but it is close enough over the exposure range of about 1 second to 1⁄1000 of a second.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Outside of this range, it becomes necessary to increase the exposure from the calculated value to account for this characteristic of the emulsion.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] This characteristic is known as *reciprocity failure*.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The film manufacturer's data sheets should be consulted to arrive at the correction required, as different emulsions have different characteristics.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Digital camera image sensors can also be subject to a form of reciprocity failure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] The Zone System is another method of determining exposure and development combinations to achieve a greater tonality range over conventional methods by varying the contrast of the film to fit the print contrast capability.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Digital cameras can achieve similar results (high dynamic range) by combining several different exposures (varying shutter or diaphragm) made in quick succession.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Today, most cameras automatically determine the correct exposure at the time of taking a photograph by using a built-in light meter, or multiple point meters interpreted by a built-in computer, see metering mode.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Negative and print film tends to bias for exposing for the shadow areas (film dislikes being starved of light), with digital favouring exposure for highlights.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Latitude is the degree by which one can over, or under expose an image, and still recover an acceptable level of quality from an exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Typically negative film has a better ability to record a range of brightness than slide/transparency film or digital.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Digital should be considered to be the reverse of print film, with a good latitude in the shadow range, and a narrow one in the highlight area; in contrast to film's large highlight latitude, and narrow shadow latitude.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Slide/Transparency film has a narrow latitude in both highlight and shadow areas, requiring greater exposure accuracy.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Negative film's latitude increases somewhat with high ISO material, in contrast digital tends to narrow on latitude with high ISO settings.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme brightness are described as having "blown-out highlights" or "flared highlights".
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] In digital images this information loss is often irreversible, though small problems can be made less noticeable using photo manipulation software.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Recording to raw image format can correct this problem to some degree, as can using a digital camera with a better sensor.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Film can often have areas of extreme overexposure but still record detail in those areas.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] This information is usually somewhat recoverable when printing or transferring to digital.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] A loss of highlights in a photograph is usually undesirable, but in some cases can be considered to "enhance" appeal.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Examples include black and white photography and portraits with an out-of-focus background.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme darkness are described as "crushed blacks".
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Digital capture tends to be more tolerant of underexposure, allowing better recovery of shadow detail, than same-ISO negative print film.
[src:tone-mapping/exposure-photography] Crushed blacks cause loss of detail, but can be used for artistic effect.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The term is often used in discussing the dynamic ranges of images, videos, audio, or radio.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] It may also apply to the means of recording, processing, and reproducing such signals including analog and digitized signals.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In this context, the term *high dynamic range* means there is a large amount of variation in light levels within a scene or an image.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The *dynamic range* refers to the range of luminosity between the brightest area and the darkest area of that scene or image.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Modern films have often been shot with cameras featuring a higher dynamic range, and legacy films can be post-converted even if manual intervention will be needed for some frames (as when black-and-white films are converted to color).
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Also, special effects, especially those that mix real and synthetic footage, require both HDR shooting and rendering.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] HDR video is also needed in applications that demand high accuracy for capturing temporal aspects of changes in the scene.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] This is important in monitoring of some industrial processes such as welding, in predictive driver assistance systems in automotive industry, in surveillance video systems, and other applications.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In photography and videography, a technique, commonly named *high dynamic range* (*HDR*) allows the dynamic range of photos and videos to be captured beyond the native capability of the camera.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] It consists of capturing multiple frames of the same scene but with different exposures and then combining them into one, resulting in an image with a dynamic range higher than the individually captured frames.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Some of the sensors on modern phones and cameras may even combine the two images on-chip.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] This also allows a wider dynamic range being directly available to the user for display or processing without in-pixel compression.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Some cameras designed for use in security applications can capture HDR videos by automatically providing two or more images for each frame, with changing exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] For example, a sensor for 30fps video will give out 60fps with the odd frames at a short exposure time and the even frames at a longer exposure time.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Modern CMOS image sensors can often capture high dynamic range images from a single exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] This reduces the need to use the multi-exposure HDR capture technique.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] High dynamic range images are used in extreme dynamic range applications like welding or automotive work.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In security cameras the term used instead of HDR is "wide dynamic range".
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Because of the nonlinearity of some sensors image artifacts can be common.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] High-dynamic-range rendering (HDRR) is the real-time rendering and display of virtual environments using a dynamic range of 65,535:1 or higher (used in computer, gaming, and entertainment technology).
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] HDRR does not require a HDR display and originally used tone mapping to display the rendering on a standard dynamic range display.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The technologies used to store, transmit, display and print images have limited dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] When captured or created images have a higher dynamic range, they must be tone mapped in order to reduce that dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] High-dynamic-range formats for image and video files are able to store more dynamic range than traditional 8-bit gamma formats.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] High dynamic range (HDR) is also the common name of a technology allowing to transmit high dynamic range videos and images to compatible displays.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] That technology also improves other aspects of transmitted images, such as color gamut.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] On January 4, 2016, the Ultra HD Alliance announced their certification requirements for an HDR display.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The HDR display must have either a peak brightness of over 1000 cd/m2 and a black level less than 0.05 cd/m2 (a contrast ratio of at least 20,000:1) or a peak brightness of over 540 cd/m2 and a black level less than 0.0005 cd/m2 (a contrast ratio of at least 1,080,000:1).
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The two options allow for different types of HDR displays such as LCD and OLED.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Some options to use HDR transfer functions that better match the human visual system other than a conventional gamma curve include the HLG and perceptual quantizer (PQ).
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] HLG and PQ require a bit depth of 10-bits per sample.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The dynamic range of a display refers to range of luminosity the display can reproduce, from the black level to its peak brightness.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The contrast of a display refers to the ratio between the luminance of the brightest white and the darkest black that a monitor can produce.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Multiple technologies allowed to increase the dynamic range of displays.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In May 2003, BrightSide Technologies demonstrated the first HDR display at the Display Week Symposium of the Society for Information Display.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] The display used an array of individually-controlled LEDs behind a conventional LCD panel in a configuration known as "local dimming".
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] BrightSide later introduced a variety of related display and video technologies enabling visualization of HDR content.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In April 2007, BrightSide Technologies was acquired by Dolby Laboratories.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In the 1970s and 1980s, Steve Mann invented the Generation-1 and Generation-2 "Digital Eye Glass" as a vision aid to help people see better with some versions being built into welding helmets for HDR vision.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In Audio, the term *high dynamic range* means there is a lot of variation in the levels of the sound.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Here, the *dynamic range* refers to the range between the highest volume and lowest volume of the sound.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] XDR (audio) is used to provide higher-quality audio when using microphone sound systems or recording onto cassette tapes.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] HDR Audio is a dynamic mixing technique used in EA Digital Illusions CE Frostbite Engine to allow relatively louder sounds to drown out softer sounds.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Dynamic range compression is a set of techniques used in audio recording and communication to put high-dynamic-range material through channels or media of lower dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Optionally, dynamic range expansion is used to restore the original high dynamic range on playback.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In radio, high dynamic range is important especially when there are potentially interfering signals.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] Measures such as spurious-free dynamic range are used to quantify the dynamic range of various system components such as frequency synthesizers.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] HDR concepts are important in both conventional and software-defined radio design.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] In many fields, instruments need to have a very high dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping/high-dynamic-range] For example, in seismology, HDR accelerometers are needed, as in the ICEARRAY instruments.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Greg Ward started developing Radiance in 1985 while at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The source code was distributed under a license forbidding further redistribution.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] In January 2002 Radiance 3.4 was relicensed under a less restrictive license.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] One study found Radiance to be the most generally useful software package for architectural lighting simulation.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The study also noted that Radiance often serves as the underlying simulation engine for many other packages.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Radiance defined an image format for storing HDR images, now described as *RGBE image format*.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Since it was the first (and for a long time the only) HDR image format, this format is supported by many other software packages.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The file starts with the signature '#?RADIANCE' and then several lines listing the commands used to generate the image.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] This information allows the renderer **rpict** to continue a partially completed render (either manually, or using the **rad** front-end).
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] There are also *key*=*value* declarations, including the line 'FORMAT=32-bit_rle_rgbe'.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] After this is a blank line signifying the end of the header.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] A single line describes the resolution and pixel order.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] As produced by the Radiance tools this always takes the form of '-Y *height* +X *width'*.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] After this line follows the binary pixel data.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Radiance calculates light values as floating point triplets, one each for red, green and blue.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] But storing a full double precision float for each channel (8 bytes × 3 = 24 bytes) is a burden even for modern systems.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Two stages are used to compress the image data.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The first scales the three floating point values to share a common 8-bit *exponent*, taken from the brightest of the three.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Each value is then truncated to an 8-bit mantissa (fractional part).
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The result is four bytes, 32 bits, for each pixel.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] This results in a 6:1 compression, at the expense of reduced colour fidelity.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The second stage performs run-length encoding on the 32-bit pixel values.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] This has a limited impact on the size of most rendered images, but it is fast and simple.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] A radiance scene is made from one or more object files.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The *.rad* format is a simple text file.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] It can specify individual geometric objects, as well as call programs by starting a line with an exclamation point '!'.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The following three lines contain parameters starting with an integer specifying the number of parameters.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The parameters need not be on the same line, they can be continued on multiple lines to aid in readability.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Modifiers create materials and can be chained together, one *modifying* the next.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] This creates a chrome material and five chrome spheres spaced 20 units apart along the X-axis.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Before a scene can be used, it must be compiled into an octree file ('.oct') using the **oconv** tool.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Most of the rendering tools (see below) use an octree file as input.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] The Radiance suite includes over 50 tools.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] They were designed for use on Unix and Unix-like systems.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Many of the tools act as filters, taking input on standard input and sending the processed result to standard output.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] These can be used on the Unix command line and piped to a new file, or included in Radiance scene files ('.rad') themselves, as shown above.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Several radiance programs manipulate Radiance scene data by reading from either a specified file or their standard input, and writing to standard output.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Generators simplify the task of modelling a scene, they create certain types of geometry from supplied parameters.
[src:tone-mapping/radiance-software] Radiance includes a number of programs for converting scene geometry from other formats.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Ibn al-Haytham gave an early explanation of color constancy by observing that the light reflected from an object is modified by the object's color.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] He explained that the quality of the light and the color of the object are mixed, and the visual system separates light and color.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Monge (1789), Young (1807), von Helmholtz (1867), Hering (1920), and von Kries (1902, 1905), as well as subsequent researchers Helson and Jeffers (1940), Judd (1940), and Land and McCann (1971), have all made significant contributions to the investigation of colour constancy.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The idea that the occurrence of colour constancy was the consequence of unconscious inference (Judd, 1940; von Helmholtz, 1867) and the idea that it was the result of sensory adaptation (Helson, 1943; Hering, 1920) coexisted for a significant portion of this time.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] To clarify the nature of observers' color-constancy judgements, Arend and Reeves (1986) conducted the first systematic behavioural experiments.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Subsequently, new colour constancy models, physiological information on cortical mechanisms, and photographic colorimetric measurements of natural scenes all appeared.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Color vision is how we perceive the objective color, which people, animals and machines are able to distinguish based on the different wavelengths of light reflected, transmitted, or emitted by the object.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] In humans, light is detected by the eye using two types of photoreceptors, cones and rods, which send signals to the visual cortex, which in turn processes those signals into a subjective perception.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Color constancy is a process that allows the brain to recognize a familiar object as being a consistent color regardless of the amount or wavelengths of light reflecting from it at a given moment.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The phenomenon of color constancy occurs when the source of illumination is not directly known.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] It is for this reason that color constancy takes a greater effect on days with sun and clear sky as opposed to days that are overcast.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Even when the sun is visible, color constancy may affect color perception.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] This is due to an ignorance of all possible sources of illumination.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Although an object may reflect multiple sources of light into the eye, color constancy causes objective identities to remain constant.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Color constancy allows for humans to interact with the world in a consistent or veridical manner and it allows for one to more effectively make judgements on the time of day.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The physiological basis for color constancy is thought to involve specialized neurons in the primary visual cortex that compute local ratios of cone activity, which is the same calculation that Land's retinex algorithm uses to achieve color constancy.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] These specialized cells are called *double-opponent cells* because they compute both color opponency and spatial opponency.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Double-opponent cells were first described by Nigel Daw in the goldfish retina.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] There was considerable debate about the existence of these cells in the primate visual system; their existence was eventually proven using reverse-correlation receptive field mapping and special stimuli that selectively activate single cone classes at a time, so-called "cone-isolating" stimuli.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Human brain imaging evidence strongly suggests that a critical cortical locus for generating color constancy is located in cortical area V4, damage in which leads to the syndrome of cerebral achromatopsia.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Color constancy works only if the incident illumination contains a range of wavelengths.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The different cone cells of the eye register different but overlapping ranges of wavelengths of the light reflected by every object in the scene.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] From this information, the visual system attempts to determine the approximate composition of the illuminating light.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] This illumination is then *discounted* in order to obtain the object's "true color" or reflectance: the wavelengths of light the object reflects.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] This reflectance then largely determines the perceived color.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] There are two possible mechanisms for color constancy.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The first mechanism is unconscious inference.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The second view holds this phenomenon to be caused by sensory adaptation.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Research suggests color constancy to be related changes in retinal cells as well as cortical areas related to vision.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] This phenomenon is most likely attributed to changes in various levels of the visual system.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Cones, specialized cells within the retina, will adjust relative to light levels within the local environment.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] This occurs at the level of individual neurons.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Chromatic adaptation is also regulated by processes within the brain.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Research in monkeys suggest that changes in chromatic sensitivity is correlated to activity in parvocellular lateral geniculate neurons.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Color constancy may be both attributed to localized changes in individual retinal cells or to higher level neural processes within the brain.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Metamerism, the perceiving of colors within two separate scenes, can help to inform research regarding color constancy.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Research suggests that when competing chromatic stimuli are presented, spatial comparisons must be completed early in the visual system.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] For example, when subjects are presented stimuli in a dichoptic fashion, an array of colors and a void color, such as grey, and are told to focus on a specific color of the array, the void color appears different than when perceived in a binocular fashion.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] This means that color judgements, as they relate to spatial comparisons, must be completed at or prior to the V1 monocular neurons.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] If spatial comparisons occur later in the visual system such as in cortical area V4, the brain would be able to perceive both the color and void color as though they were seen in a binocular fashion.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Land, who was attempting to reconstruct James Clerk Maxwell's early experiments in full-colored images.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Land saw that, even when only yellow light illuminated the superimposed images, the visual system would still perceive a full (if muted) range of color.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Land described this effect in a 1959 article in *Scientific American.* In 1977, Land wrote another *Scientific American* article that described a generalized Land effect, leading to formulation of his "Retinex Theory" to explain what he believed was main basis of human color vision.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The word "retinex" is a blend of "retina" and "cortex", suggesting that both the eye and the brain are involved in the processing.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The generalized Land effect can be experimentally demonstrated as follows.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] A display called a "Mondrian" (after Piet Mondrian whose paintings are similar) consisting of numerous colored patches is shown to a person.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The display is illuminated by three white lights, one projected through a red filter, one projected through a green filter, and one projected through a blue filter.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The person is asked to adjust the intensity of the lights so that a particular patch in the display appears white.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The experimenter then measures the intensities of red, green, and blue light reflected from this white-appearing patch.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Then the experimenter asks the person to identify the color of a neighboring patch, which, for example, appears green.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Then the experimenter adjusts the lights so that the intensities of red, blue, and green light reflected from the green patch are the same as were originally measured from the white patch.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The person shows color constancy in that the green patch continues to appear green, the white patch continues to appear white, and all the remaining patches continue to have their original colors.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Land, with John McCann, also developed a computer program designed to imitate the retinex processes thought to be taking place in human physiology.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Color constancy is a desirable feature of computer vision, and many algorithms have been developed for this purpose.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] These include several retinex algorithms.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] These algorithms receive as input the red/green/blue values of each pixel of the image and attempt to estimate the reflectances of each point.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] One such algorithm operates as follows: the maximal red value *r*max of all pixels is determined, and also the maximal green value *g**max* and the maximal blue value *b*max.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Assuming that the scene contains objects which reflect all red light, and (other) objects which reflect all green light and still others which reflect all blue light, one can then deduce that the illuminating light source is described by (*r*max, *g*max, *b*max).
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] For each pixel with values (*r*, *g*, *b*) its reflectance is estimated as (*r*/*r*max, *g*/*g*max, *b*/*b*max).
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] The original retinex algorithm proposed by Land and McCann uses a localized version of this principle.
[src:tone-mapping/retinex] Although retinex models are still widely used in computer vision, actual human color perception has been shown to be more complex.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The introduction of film-based photography created issues since capturing the wide dynamic range of lighting from the real world on a chemically limited negative was very difficult.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Early film developers attempted to remedy this issue by designing film stocks and print development systems that gave a desired S-shaped tone curve with slightly enhanced contrast (about 15%) in the middle range and gradually compressed highlights and shadows .
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Photographers have also used dodging and burning to overcome the limitations of the print process .
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The advent of digital photography gave hope for better solutions to this problem.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] One of the earliest algorithms employed by Land and McCann in 1971 was Retinex, inspired by theories of lightness perception .This method is inspired by the eye’s biological mechanisms of adaptation when lighting conditions are an issue.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Gamut mapping algorithms were also extensively studied in the context of color printing.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Computational models such as CIECAM02 or iCAM were used to predict color appearance.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Despite this, if algorithms could not sufficiently map tones and colors, a skilled artist was still needed, as is the case with cinematographic movie post-processing.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Computer graphic techniques capable of rendering high-contrast scenes shifted the focus from color to luminance as the main limiting factor of display devices.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Several tone mapping operators were developed to map high dynamic range images to standard displays.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] More recently, this work has branched away from utilizing luminance to extend image contrast and towards other methods such as user-assisted image reproduction.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Currently, image reproduction has shifted towards display-driven solutions since displays now possess advanced image processing algorithms that help adapt rendering of the image to viewing conditions, save power, up-scale color gamut and dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The goals of tone mapping can be differently stated depending on the particular application.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] In some cases producing just aesthetically pleasing images is the main goal, while other applications might emphasize reproducing as many image details as possible, or maximizing the image contrast.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The goal in realistic rendering applications might be to obtain a perceptual match between a real scene and a displayed image even though the display device is not able to reproduce the full range of luminance values.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Various tone mapping operators have been developed in the recent years.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] A simple example of global tone mapping filter is $V_{\text{out}}={\frac {V_{\text{in}}}{V_{\text{in}}+1}}$ (Reinhard), where *V*in is the luminance of the original pixel and *V*out is the luminance of the filtered pixel.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Variations on this filter are commonly used in rendering.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] A perhaps more useful global tone mapping method is gamma compression, which has the filter $V_{\text{out}}=A\,V_{\text{in}}^{\gamma },$ where *A* > 0 and 0 < *γ* < 1.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] This function will map the luminance *V*in in the domain $[0,A^{-1/\gamma }]$ to the output range $[0,1].$ *γ* regulates the contrast of the image; a lower value for lower contrast.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] While a lower constant *γ* gives a lower contrast and perhaps also a duller image, it increases the exposure of underexposed parts of the image while at the same time, if *A* < 1, it can decrease the exposure of overexposed parts of the image enough to prevent them from being overexposed.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] An even more sophisticated group of tone mapping algorithms is based on contrast or gradient domain methods, which are 'local'.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Such operators concentrate on preserving contrast between neighboring regions rather than absolute value, an approach motivated by the fact that the human perception is most sensitive to contrast in images rather than absolute intensities.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Those tone mapping methods usually produce very sharp images, which preserve very well small contrast details; however, this is often done at the cost of flattening an overall image contrast, and may as a side effect produce halo-like glows around dark objects.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Examples of such tone mapping methods include: gradient domain high dynamic range compression and A Perceptual Framework for Contrast Processing of High Dynamic Range Images (a tone mapping is one of the applications of this framework).
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Another approach to tone mapping of HDR images is inspired by the anchoring theory of lightness perception.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] This theory explains many characteristics of the human visual system such as lightness constancy and its failures (as in the checker shadow illusion), which are important in the perception of images.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The key concept of this tone mapping method (Lightness Perception in Tone Reproduction) is a decomposition of an HDR image into areas (frameworks) of consistent illumination and the local calculation of the lightness values.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The net lightness of an image is calculated by merging of the frameworks proportionally to their strength.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Particularly important is the anchoring—relating of the luminance to a known luminance, namely estimating which luminance value is perceived as white in the scene.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] This approach to tone mapping does not affect the local contrast and preserves the natural colors of an HDR image due to the linear handling of luminance.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] One simple form of tone mapping takes a standard image (not HDR –the dynamic range already compressed) and applies unsharp masking with a large radius, which increases local contrast rather than sharpening.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] See unsharp masking: local contrast enhancement for details.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] One of the commonly used tone mapping algorithms is the iCAM06 which is based on both the color appearance model and hierarchical mapping.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] After bilateral filtering, the image is broken into a base layer and a detail layer.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] White point adaptation and chrominance adaptation are applied to the base layer, while detail enhancement is applied to the detail layer.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Eventually the two layers are merged and converted to the IPT color space.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] In general, this method is good but has some shortcomings, specifically in how computationally heavy the filtering method is.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] A proposed solution to this involves performance optimization of the filter.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The base layer of the image is also converted to the RGB space for tone compression.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] This method also allows for more output adjustment and saturation enhancement, making it be less computationally intensive and better at reducing the overall halo effect.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Forms of tone mapping long precede digital photography.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The manipulation of film and development process to render high contrast scenes, especially those shot in bright sunlight, on printing paper with a relatively low dynamic range, is effectively a form of tone mapping, although it is not usually called that.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Local adjustment of tonality in film processing is primarily done via dodging and burning, and is particularly advocated by and associated with Ansel Adams, as described in his book *The Print;* see also his Zone System.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The normal process of exposure compensation, brightening shadows and altering contrast applied globally to digital images as part of a professional or serious amateur workflow is also a form of tone mapping.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] There are now many examples of locally tone mapped digital images, inaccurately known as "HDR photographs", on the internet, and these are of varying quality.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Although digital sensors actually capture a higher dynamic range than film, they completely lose detail in extreme highlights, clipping them to pure white, producing an unattractive result when compared with negative film, which tends to retain color and some detail in highlights.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] In some cases, tone mapped images are produced from a single exposure which is then manipulated with conventional processing tools to produce the inputs to the HDR image generation process.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] This avoids the artifacts that can appear when different exposures are combined, due to moving objects in the scene or camera shake.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] However, when tone mapping is applied to a single exposure in this way, the intermediate image has only normal dynamic range, and the amount of shadow or highlight detail that can be rendered is only that which was captured in the original exposure.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] One of the original goals of tone mapping was to be able to reproduce a given scene or image onto a display device such that the brightness sensation of the image to a human viewer closely matches the real-world brightness sensation.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] However, a perfect match for this problem is never possible and thus the output image on a display is often built from a tradeoff between different image features.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Choosing between features is often based on the necessary application, and given appropriate metrics for the application, one possible solution is to treat the issue as an optimization problem.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] For this method, models for the Human Visual System (HVS) and the display are first generated, along with a simple tone mapping operator.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The contrast distortions are weighted according to their individual visibilities approximated by the HVS.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] With these models, an objective function that defines the tone curve can be created and solved using a fast quadratic solver.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] With the addition of filters, this method can also be extended to videos.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The filters ensure that the rapid changing of the tone-curve between frames are not salient in the final output image.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The images on the right show the interior of a church, a scene which has a variation in radiance much larger than that which can be displayed on a monitor or recorded by a conventional camera.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The six individual exposures from the camera show the radiance of the scene in some range transformed to the range of brightnesses that can be displayed on a monitor.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The range of radiances recorded in each photo is limited, so not all details can be displayed at once: for example, details of the dark church interior cannot be displayed at the same time as those of the bright stained-glass window.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] An algorithm is applied to the six images to recreate the high dynamic range radiance map of the original scene (a high dynamic range image).
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Alternatively, some higher-end consumer and specialist scientific digital cameras are able to record a high dynamic range image directly, for example with RAW images.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] The high dynamic range image is passed to a tone mapping operator, in this case a local operator, which transforms the image into a low dynamic range image suitable for viewing on a monitor.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Relative to the church interior, the stained-glass window is displayed at a much lower brightness than a linear mapping between scene radiance and pixel intensity would produce.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] However, this inaccuracy is perceptually less important than the image detail, which can now be shown in both the window and the church interior simultaneously.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] These results are caused by application of geometric space distortion of captured image along with color space distortion, while only color space distortions are a tone mapping effect, and all other distortions are rather a custom filtering technique than any tone or color space mapping.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] So, the results of local tone mapping are often judged as perverting the nature of a documentalist photographic image and far from photographic realism.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Not all tone mapped images are visually distinctive.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Reducing dynamic range with tone mapping is often useful in bright sunlit scenes, where the difference in intensity between direct illumination and shadow is great.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] In these cases the global contrast of the scene is reduced, but the local contrast maintained, while the image as a whole continues to look natural.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Tone mapping can also produce distinctive visual effects in the final image, such as the visible halo around the tower in the Cornell Law School image in the thumbnail.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] It can be used to produce these effects even when the dynamic range of the original image is not particularly high.
[src:tone-mapping/tone-mapping] Usually this effect is subtle, but if the contrasts in the original image are extreme, or the photographer deliberately sets the luminance gradient to be very steep, the halos become visible.
